This EF-1 tornado began near the intersection of US Highway 11 and MS Highway 528, initially mainly producing damage to tree limbs as it tracked across southeast Jasper County. Along CR 642, the roof of a mobile home was damaged and trees were uprooted. The tornado strengthened after crossing into Clarke County, producing a concentrated path of snapped trees as it crossed CR 250 west of the Goodwater community. Additional tree limb damage occurred along CR 280 before the tornado lifted near the Nancy community. Max wind 105 mph, path length 9.1 miles, maximum path width 300 yards.

An EF-1 tornado touched down in the Carson community in Jefferson Davis County. The tornado started just south of Carson on King Lane and tracked northeast crossing Highway 42 on the east side of Carson. There was significant tree and vegetation damage along Old Highway 42 and Alex Daley Road. Numerous trees were uprooted and snapped along Alex Daley Road. A chicken farm was hit just off of Alex Daley Road and sustained substantial damage. Most of the homes in this area had very little structural damage. The tornado continued northeast crossing Haw Pond Road and Highway 35 causing more tree damage. The tornado then continued to Santee Baptist Church Road where it damaged another chicken farm and continued to cause more tree damage. The tornado ended just beyond Santee Baptist Church Road in a wooded area. Max wind 100 mph, path length 4. 8 miles, max path width 350 yards.

Around midnight on January 10th, 2026 a supercell thunderstorm was moving toward the town of Coushatta. Rotation then quickly developed near HWY 480, several miles south of Coushatta, moving east. A tornado briefly touched down on HWY 71 near the Rolling Hills Trailer Park. Fortunately, no structural damage was found, however, multiple large branches were snapped off of nearby softwood trees and several hardwood trees were found uprooted and with large branches snapped right along the highway. As the tornado crossed HWY 71, it moved into a field where additional softwood trees were found uprooted and snapped. The tornado likely then lifted as it moved farther into the field/heavily wooded rural area. Some wind damage was then found in the Grand Bayou Resort campground area, with a few large branches off of nearby trees blown down.
